metadata.name: Magic Totem #87
metadata.description:
These magic totems carry with them a unique combination of symbols that will be generated by you at the time of the mint. The symbols channel energy from nature through the elements contained in the horns, in the prints and in the colors taken from a natural palette. The entire construction of this project was thought to make the totems look like they were handmade, carefully and personally sewn for each owner.

Go to Live View ("open live") and press 's' to save your totem.

Code wruted by @ltnft21
Illustration by @polilustra

metadata.name: Moir√©_Ellipses_Dark #6
metadata.description:
This is a companion piece to https://www.fxhash.xyz/generative/3831 - Moir√©_Ellipses_Light. There's little difference between the two aside from palette choice, and variation is somewhat limited.

Between four and six elliptical rings rotate in alternately contrary directions. Each ellipse is bounded within by a further ellipse, and between these two points, striations are marked at a slight angle. The resulting motion produces emergent Moir√© patterns.

The number of ellipses, their segmentation level and colour are all generated from hash. The eccentricity of the inner and outer ellipses is also hash-generated, resulting in uniquely beautiful images.

This version features lighter hues and a darker background.

metadata.name: Acequia #110
metadata.description:
Acequia (‚Äúah-seh-kee-uh‚Äù) - a Spanish adaptation of the Arabic word as-sƒÅqiya, meaning ‚Äúwater carrier‚Äù. 

In our second collaboration, Rich and Rick are back with our blend of generative code, intricate design, attention to detail, and a splash of charm. 

‚Ä®Acequias are traditional irrigation canals used to distribute rainwater and snowmelt along a complex network of narrow channels. They are found in Spain, the American Southwest, and northern Mexico, where they are essential for sustaining fields, orchards, and gardens in semi-arid regions. ‚Ä®‚Ä®
Our aim in this series is to capture the essence of these waterways in bold geometric designs. Each piece is inspired by a mountain village or town in Andalusia (southern Spain). 

The location determines the cube designs and construction rules that are used to build the final output. These are combined with striking day/night palettes, outline styles, scales, climates, and a few surprises of course!


Controls (in live view): 

- Press [p] to pause water animation 
- Press [e] to complete water animation 
- Press [r] to reset water animation 
- Press [s] to save the current image 
- Press [h] for a high-res output suitable for printing 
- Press [b] to toggle the border

metadata.name: enter the dragon #11
metadata.description:
This generative token uses a modified fractal algorithm based on the Dragon Curve.
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dragon_curve

Random colours and radius are used to visualize the pattern.


color scheme: 14 variations of sets of 4 colours
start angle: first direction, between 0 and 90
loops: how many iterations to pre-compute, between 7 and 15
angle: the angle of each turn, between 85 and 90
frames: total number of frames before the animation stops. Between 2500 and 5000.
alpha: alpha value used for some transparency. Between 200 and 250.

metadata.name: Fleur des Sinus #84
metadata.description:
Originally based on Alberto Burri's 1973- 1976 Screen Prints, then further iterated upon: Fleur des Sinus is meant to play with abstraction by designing larger than the canvas. Creating something that's clearly defined and pushing in just enough to find new compositions in section and intersection.

There are two possible modes, changing the shape of the flowers.
26 palettes are available, each composed of 4 colors: 104 colors in total.
A palette is picked for each edge flower, the center flower expresses itself with no inhibitions.
The Flowers are made up of between 4-10 petals.
The background pattern is 1-6 petal minimal dot flower patterns.

Press 's' to save the image in Live View.

metadata.name: Papercut imitation #5
metadata.description:
This art imitate the "Papercut technique" in vector illustration.
100% generative art - no additional sources used. Code only.
Features:
- 5 color palettes
- random number of layers (from 2 to 4) and random shape of layers
- random additional cut in upper layer
- rare appearance of moon
- rare appearance of crescent with a star
- very rare appearance of crescent with 2 stars
- random tree shape
